  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT45-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">talaimakaṟkup pāṅkāyiṉāyiṉār vāyil vēṇṭiyavaḻit tōḻi vāyil nērntatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">The confidante granting mediation/the door, when those close to HIM wished for mediation/the door.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT45">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                kālai yeḻuntu kaṭuntēr paṇṇi</l>
<l>                vāliḻai makaḷirt taḻīiya ceṉṟa</l>
<l>                malla lūra ṉelliṉaṉ periteṉa</l>
<l>                maṟuvaruñ ciṟuvaṉ ṟāyē</l>
<l>                teṟuva tammavit tiṇaippiṟat tallē.</l>

             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
             <l rend="indent">Risen in the morning, after preparing the swift chariot,</l>
             <l rend="indent">[he's] gone to embrace women with pure ornaments (?) </l>
             <l rend="indent">“Very glorious [is] the man from the prosperous village”,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">peritu</term> seems to be an adverb in emphatic postposition. Moreover, given the context of the poem, we cannot but read this line as an ironical statement.</note></l>
             <l rend="indent4">[thinking] thus</l>
             <l>the little one's mother is agitated.</l>
             <l>Painful, alas, to be born into this family.</l>
             <lg type="alternate" resp="#Srin" sameAs="5b">
                <l>Painful, alas, to be born into this sex (as a woman).<note place="foot">In the first interpretation the speaker rather seems to express pity for the child arisen from this relationship than pity for HER. The second, <term xml:lang="ta">tiṇai</term> as "sex", is tendentious and may be anachronistic; but see NA 94 where SHE complains about the difference in the rules set up for men and women.</note></l>
             </lg>
                </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
